item.title: China Casts CIA as Villain in New Anti-Spying Push
item.description: State-security ministry accuses two Chinese citizens of spying for U.S. as espionage fears grip both countries.

item.title: European Natural Gas Prices Slump as Woodside Deal Averts Strike in LNG Facility
item.description: European natural gas prices slumped after a last-minute deal at a key Australian LNG export facility appears to have prevented a strike.

item.title: Russian Court Extends Pretrial Detention of Jailed WSJ Reporter
item.description: Evan Gershkovich, detained on an espionage charge since March, will remain in a Russian jail until at least Nov. 30.

item.title: Japan Starts Releasing Water From Fukushima Nuclear Plant Into Pacific
item.description: Japan plans to release more than 1.3 million tons of water with small quantities of radioactive tritium over some three decades.

item.title: Metals Slip Amid Worries Over China Demand
item.description: Base metals prices were falling but gold edged higher in early London trading, as worries around China’s property sector continued to pressure industrial goods.

item.title: Dollar Could Fall as Risk Appetite Improves, Jobless Claims in Focus
item.description: The safe-haven dollar could edge lower as equities rose following strong Nvidia results, ING said, and focus turns to jobless claims data.

item.title: End of Interest-Rate Rises Would Be Positive for Eurozone Government Bonds
item.description: Eurozone government bonds are expected to deliver higher returns in the remainder of the year in light of yields declining, UniCredit Research said.

item.title: Tencent-Backed VNG Targets About $150 Million in U.S. IPO
item.description: EXCLUSIVE: Vietnamese internet company VNG aims to raise roughly $150 million in a U.S. initial public offering that could take place as soon as next month, according to people familiar with the matter.

item.title: China Suspends Imports of Aquatic Products From Japan
item.description: China’s customs bureau will suspend all imports of aquatic products from Japan in response to the release of wastewater from the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear plant.

item.title: Credit Suisse Drops Real-Estate Fund IPO Plan
item.description: Credit Suisse said it has abandoned its plan to launch an initial public offering for its Credit Suisse 1a Immo PK real-estate fund due to low trading volumes for listed Swiss real-estate funds.

item.title: Engie Buys Texas Battery-Storage Firm
item.description: Engie signed a binding agreement to buy Broad Reach Power from EnCap and Apollo for an undisclosed sum.

item.title: Norwegian Air Profit Falls, But Demand Remains Strong
item.description: Norwegian Air Shuttle reported a drop in second-quarter net profit to NOK538 million, but said demand was strong and that it has begun examining the potential for a dividend.

item.title: Building Green: New Technologies to Create Less Polluting Cement
item.description: Roughly 7% of all CO2 emissions come from cement production, and with populations rising, more buildings are going to be needed.

item.title: A Very Good Republican Presidential Debate
item.description: Without Trump, the candidates could fight about their policies.

item.title: Nikkei Rises 0.9%, Led by Electronics, Tech Stocks
item.description: Japanese stocks ended higher, led by gains in electronics and tech stocks, as Nvidia’s strong results spurred buying into chip-related stocks and as concerns eased about borrowing costs.

item.title: Giuliani turned himself in to Georgia authorities and was booked on charges that he led an effort to illegally keep Trump in power, after negotiating a $150,000 bond.

item.title: Stocks rose, as the S&P 500 gained 1.1% in its best daily performance since June. The Dow was up 0.5% and the Nasdaq 1.6%.
